\begin{abstract}
Let $A\subset\R^2$ be an infinite set in \emph{general position} (no three points collinear, no four concyclic), and let $G_A$ be the graph on $A$ joining pairs of points at integer Euclidean distance. We study how large the clique number $\omega(G_A)$ and the chromatic number $\chi(G_A)$ can be. We prove, with complete and self-contained arguments: (1)~every clique of $G_A$ is finite, via a quantitative self-contained proof of the Anning--Erd\H{o}s theorem; (2)~$\chi(G_A)\le\aleph_0$ for every admissible $A$, of any cardinality; (3)~an exact transfer principle: some admissible $A$ has $\chi(G_A)=\aleph_0$ if and only if finite admissible configurations of unbounded chromatic number exist, and likewise for clique sizes, where the construction direction rests on a generic rigid-motion placement lemma proved here; and (4)~explicit, exactly verified certificates: a six-point set in general position with all fifteen pairwise distances integral, giving $\omega,\chi\ge 6$. Whether $\chi$ can equal $\aleph_0$ is thereby shown to be \emph{equivalent} to the open Erd\H{o}s problem of whether integral point sets in general position exist at every finite size; we do not claim to resolve that problem in either direction. An appendix documents the exact-arithmetic verification.
\end{abstract}

